  "opinion": "As a retired electrician who's spent decades fixing wires and circuits, I've learned that the most reliable tools are the ones you can trust. When it comes to managing fake content on social media, I've found that the same principles apply—just like checking a circuit for a short before touching it. I spend about an hour each day on social media, mostly to stay connected with family and friends, but I've also noticed how quickly misinformation can spread. My approach is simple: first, I verify the source. If a post seems too good to be true or comes from an unfamiliar account, I don't share it right away. I often check with my daughter, who's a teacher and knows a lot about how schools handle misinformation. She's taught me to look for credible news outlets and cross-reference facts. Another thing that helps is being mindful of the time. I've learned to set specific times for checking social media, like after I finish my morning routine, so I don't get caught up in the news cycle. I also try to focus on positive content—like posts from local community groups or family updates—that actually bring people together. My faith in Christianity has also been a big part of my approach; it reminds me to think before I act and to seek truth in all things. I've seen how even small actions, like sharing a verified fact, can make a difference. So, for me, managing fake content isn't about avoiding social media entirely—it's about being intentional and thoughtful, just like I am when I'm working on a circuit.",
